04684nam a2200637Ia 9781501731419DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20181996nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017314197 a10.7591/97815017314192doi  a(DE-B1597)515652  a(OCoLC)1129169769  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aPOL0420202bisacsh04a324.2/182/0942201 aKalyvas, Stathis N., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Rise of Christian Democracy in Europe /cStathis N. Kalyvas. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2018] 4c©1996  a1 online resource (344 p.) :b4 drawings, 4 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Wilder House series in politics, history, and culture00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: The Christian Democratic Phenomenon -- t1. Actors and Preferences -- t2. Strategies and Outcomes -- t3. The Puzzle of Nonformation: The Case of France -- t4. The Formation of Confessional Parties in Historical Context -- t5. After the Formation: The Confessional Dilemma and the Construction of a Catholic Political Identity -- tConclusion: Toward a Theory of Christian Democracy -- tReferences -- tSubject Index -- tAuthor Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAlthough dominant in West European politics for more than a century, Christian Democratic parties remain largely unexplored and little understood. An investigation of how political identities and parties form, this book considers the origins of Christian Democratic "confessional" parties within the political context of Western Europe. Examining five countries where a successful confessional party emerged (Belgium, the Netherlands, Austria, Germany, and Italy) and one where it did not (France), Stathis N. Kalyvas addresses perplexing questions raised by the Christian Democratic phenomenon. How can we reconcile the religious roots of these parties with their tremendous success and resilience in secular and democratic Western Europe? Why have these parties discarded their initial principles and objectives to become secular forces governing secular societies? The author's answers reveal the way in which social and political actors make decisions based on self-interest under conditions that constrain their choices and the information they rely on—often with unintended but irrevocable consequences.Kalyvas also lays a foundation for a theory of the Christian Democratic phenomenon which would specify the conditions under which confessional parties succeed and would determine the impact of such parties, and the way they are formed, on politics and society. Drawing from political science, sociology, and history, his analysis goes beyond Christian Democracy to address issues related to the methodology of political science, the theory of party formation, the political development of Europe, the relationship between religion and politics, the construction of collective political identities, and the role of agency and contingency in politics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aChristian democratic partieszEuropexHistory. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 4aReligious Studies. 4aWest European History. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Ideologies / Conservatism & Liberalism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Archive Pre-2000z978311053617140uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150173141940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501731419423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501731419/original  a978-3-11-053617-1  Cornell University Press Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aE